			"contents": "# April 15\n\n## Maximum Likelihood and Bayesian Methods\n\nMaximum Likelihood and Bayesian Methods are the two methods predominantly in use today for the analysis of molecular data for inferring phylogenies. They are both based on the concept of likelihood, or the probability of observing the data given some model.\n\nIn this case, for Maximum Likelihood it is the probability of observing the sequence data given the model of DNA evolution and the topology. We donʻt start off knowing all of the parameters for the model of evolution, nor the topology, we fit the parameters to the data, and search over many many possible topologies until we find the maximum likelihood tree. So specifying the model ends up being choosing how many parameters are included in the model and for what blocks of the data.  In maximum likelihood, the \"best\" model is the one that provides the greatest probability of observing the data, given the model (including evolutionary model and topology).\n\n\n42. __Felsenstein, J. 2004__ Chapter 16 Likelihood Methods. Pp. 248-274 in Inferring Phylogenies. Sinauer Assoc., Sunderland.  **todos:Manuel,Taren**\n\nInstead of concept maps, Iʻd like you to be prepared to discuss the following. Donʻt freak out about the math. Please try to understand problem and what information they are using to solve the problem. Focus on the approach and be prepared to explain to the group.\n\nTo Dos:\nRun through Computing the likelihood of a tree up til Economising - Manuel  \nFinding the maximum likelihood tree - Taren  \nInferring ancestral sequences and unrootedness - Manuel  \nRates varying among sites and HMMs - Taren  \nModels with clocks, relaxed clocks, models - Manuel  \nMis/better behavior with the wrong model - Taren  \n\n\n\n\n",
